<answer> Solving the equations in pairs, we get
\begin{align*}
\left\{
\begin{align*}
y = \frac{1}{2}x + 3\\
y = -2x + 6
\end{align*}
\right.& \implies x = 2, y = 4
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
\left\{
\begin{align*}
y = \frac{1}{2}x + 3\\
y = 1
\end{align*}
\right.& \implies x = -4, y = 1
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
\left\{
\begin{align*}
y = -2x + 6\\
y = 1
\end{align*}
\right.& \implies x = \frac{5}{2}, y = 1
\end{align*} 
Therefore, the vertices of the triangle are $(2,4)$, $(-4,1)$, and $(\frac{5}{2},1)$. The base of the triangle is the distance between $(-4,1)$ and $(\frac{5}{2},1)$, which is $9$. The height of the triangle is the $y$-coordinate of $(2,4)$, which is $4$. 
Thus, the area of the triangle is $\frac{1}{2} \cdot 9 \cdot 4 = 18$. 
